  "explanation": [
    {
      "heading": "Why Consistent Hashing?",
      "body": "Naive: `server = hash(key) % N`. Add/remove a server, N changes → **almost every key remaps**.\n\nConsistent hashing: arrange servers on a circular ring. Each key maps to the **first server clockwise** from its hash position.",
      "appearsAtStep": 0
    },
    {
      "heading": "Adding a Server",
      "body": "Adding Server D between A and B on the ring only moves **keys that were between A and D**.\n\nOnly those keys now belong to D. All other keys remain with their current servers.\n\nRatio of keys moved: `1/N` on average (where N = new total servers).",
      "appearsAtStep": 2
    },
    {
      "heading": "Removing a Server",
      "body": "Removing Server B: only B's keys need to move — they shift to the **next server clockwise** (C).\n\nAgain, only ~1/N of all keys are affected.\n\nThis is the key property: **minimal disruption** during topology changes.",
      "appearsAtStep": 3
    },
    {
      "heading": "Virtual Nodes",
      "body": "Problem: with few servers, key distribution can be uneven (hot spots).\n\nSolution: each physical server gets **V virtual nodes** on the ring, with different hash positions.\n\nMore virtual nodes = smoother distribution. Cassandra defaults to 256 virtual nodes per server.",
      "appearsAtStep": 4
    }
  ],
